/-!
# Sawin: An explicit lower bound for the unit distance problem

*Reference:* [arxiv/2605.20579](https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.20579)
**An explicit lower bound for the unit distance problem**
by *Will Sawin* (2026).

Sawin gives the first explicit lower bound exponent for the disproof of Erd≈ës's unit-distance
conjecture (see `FormalConjectures.ErdosProblems.¬´90¬ª`): there exist arbitrarily large finite point
sets in `‚Ñù¬≤` with at least `n^{1.014114} / C` unit-distance pairs. The proof factors through three
self-contained reductions, each posed below as its own benchmark challenge:

* `Sawin.lemma_2_lattice_to_unit_distances` ‚Äî pure geometry of numbers; given a lattice in
  `‚Ñù^{2d}`, a projection to `‚Ñù¬≤`, and a family of "matching" lattice vectors of bounded norm
  projecting to the unit circle, extract a planar point set with high unit-distance density.
* `Sawin.lemmas_11_12_tower` ‚Äî existence of an infinite tower of totally real number fields with
  bounded root discriminant and prescribed split primes; this is where the Golod‚ÄìShafarevich
  inequality and the Hajir‚ÄìMaire‚ÄìRamakrishna (2003) construction enter.
* `Sawin.theorem_1_explicit_lower_bound` ‚Äî the main theorem assembled from the above.
-/

